column30:
I have attended a number of phython sessions, and I tried three different types of teaching:
1) fully autonomous, everyone works their codes alone and asks questions
2) fully guided, the teacher walks through the code and solutions in class
3) hybrid, where the teacher gives an overview of the class content (set-up expectations) and then each student works on the materials alone and asks if questions arise. 

Personally, I prefer approach 3, as this allows the students to go at their own pace but have the chance to ask for clarification whilst knowing what to expect from the class from the start.

column37: Without online workshops, I'd not have been able to benefit from most of them. There are just so many situations where it's not possible for me to attend in-person workshops, even without the covid-19-situation. Example 1: on some days I do not have classes at the LSE, so I'd need to travel for 40 minutes to and 40 minutes back from School (which also costs money) just to attend a 1-hour workshop. Example 2: sometimes my Schedule is so tight, that simply traveling from one part of campus to the next would make me miss the first 10 minutes of the workshop. Example 3: since 70% of LSE's students are international students, most of them travel to their parent's home after finishing summer exams (e.g. to work on dissertation etc). That's the time when we have the most free time to make use of the DSL workshops, but we cannot attend in-person classes.
